  "prompt": "If we evolved from apes then why are there still apes around today?",
  "response": "The idea that humans evolved from apes is a common misconception. Here's a more accurate explanation:\n\nHumans and modern apes (like chimpanzees, bonobos, gorillas, and orangutans) share a common ancestor that lived millions of years ago. This common ancestor was neither a modern human nor a modern ape, but an ancient primate species. Over time, different lineages of this ancestor diversified and evolved into the various species of apes and humans we see today.\n\nThink of it like a family tree: humans and modern apes are like cousins, both descended from a shared ancestor, rather than one evolving directly from the other. Evolution is a branching process, not a linear one. When one species splits into two or more species, it doesn't mean the original species disappears. Instead, each population may adapt to different environments and evolve in unique ways.\n\nFor example, one population of the common ancestor might have adapted to life in forests, leading to modern apes, while another population might have evolved traits suited for walking on two legs and using tools, leading to humans. This process is called **speciation**, and it explains why both humans and apes exist today.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
